## Project overview



For our problem, the domain for the electric field ğ‘‰ is the unit interval ğ‘¥âˆˆ[0,1], with boundary conditions ğ‘‰(ğ‘¥=0)=0 and ğ‘‰(ğ‘¥=1)=1. The Laplace equation to solve is

ğ‘‘ğ‘‘ğ‘¥[ğœ–(ğ‘¥)ğ‘‘ğ‘‰ğ‘‘ğ‘¥]=0

where the inhomogeneous dielectric constant is (in arbitrary units) given by

ğœ–(ğ‘¥)=1+10cos2(2ğœ‹ğ‘¥)

Use a discretization scheme where the ğ‘¥ axis will be discretized into ğ‘+1 points, such that ğ‘¥ğ‘–=ğ‘–Î”ğ‘¥, with Î”ğ‘¥=1/ğ‘.  

The boundary conditions become ğ‘‰0=0 and ğ‘‰ğ‘=1.

The discretization of this Laplace equation needs to take into account the ğ‘¥ dependence of ğœ–. To ğ‘‚(Î”ğ‘¥2) , this works out as follows:

ğ‘‘ğ‘‘ğ‘¥[ğœ–(ğ‘¥)ğ‘‘ğ‘‰ğ‘‘ğ‘¥]ğ‘¥=ğ‘¥ğ‘–

â‰ˆğœ–(ğ‘¥+Î”ğ‘¥/2)ğ‘‰ğ‘–+1+ğœ–(ğ‘¥âˆ’Î”ğ‘¥/2)ğ‘‰ğ‘–âˆ’1âˆ’{ğœ–(ğ‘¥+Î”ğ‘¥/2)+ğœ–(ğ‘¥âˆ’Î”ğ‘¥/2)}ğ‘‰ğ‘–Î”ğ‘¥2

This holds for ğ‘–>0 and ğ‘–<ğ‘. 

If we denote by ğ‘£ the ğ‘âˆ’1-dimensional vector (ğ‘‰1,ğ‘‰2,..,ğ‘‰ğ‘âˆ’1), we can write the discretized equation as

ğ€â‹…ğ‘£=ğ‘

where ğ€ is an ğ‘âˆ’1 x ğ‘âˆ’1 "tri-diagonal" matrix, and ğ‘ is an ğ‘âˆ’1 dimensional vector (0,...,0,âˆ’ğœ–(ğ‘¥+Î”ğ‘¥/2)ğ‘‰ğ‘/Î”ğ‘¥2) (that is, unless you factor out the common factor of 1/Î”ğ‘¥2).




## Compiler and Library


Compiler: g++ 13.2.0

RARRAY
git clone https://github.com/dkirkby/rarray.git

HDF5
git clone https://github.com/HDFGroup/hdf5.git
cd hdf5
./configure --prefix=/path/to/installation/directory
make
make install

NetCDF
git clone https://github.com/Unidata/netcdf-c.git
cd netcdf-c
./configure --prefix=/path/to/installation/directory
make
make install


OpenBLAS

git clone https://github.com/xianyi/OpenBLAS.git openblasbuild
cd openblasbuild
git checkout v0.3.21
make USE_LOCKING=1 USE_OPENMP=0 USE_THREAD=0
make PREFIX=~/MyOpenBLAS install



## Background

Lecture notes on Modular Programming. 

## Description of files


- `laplacesolver.cpp`: Main executable, takes 1 inputs: N the number of steps along x. The default value is 10000. Stores the value into output.nc file.
- `output.nc`:  Contains the output of ./1dlaplacesolve
- `Makefile`: Allows compiling with  `make` or clean with `make clean` and produces output files: `[name_file].o`, which are used to produced the executable file: `1dlaplacesolver`
- `1dlaplacesolver`: Executable file (see Usage)
- `[name_file]~`: Automatic copy of the file: [name_file].

